---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="The Book"
  description="A book for software developers on human skills, working better, and thriving in tech. By Leaf (Jessica Roy)."
>
  <div class="page book-page">
    <h1 class="page-title">The book</h1>

    <section class="book-intro">
      <p>I'm writing a book for software developers. It's generated a lot of questions!</p>
    </section>

    <section class="book-content">
      <h2>What's the book about?</h2>
      <p>
        Imagine you're a developer looking at what seems to be the top rung of your career ladder.
        You'd like to keep growing and progressing in your career, but you're not so sure you want
        to be a people manager.
      </p>
      <p>What do you do? What should you learn?</p>
      <p>
        I've been a developer for 20 years, and I've learned a lot along the way. I'd like to share
        those lessons to help other developers grow in their careers.
      </p>

      <h2>Do you have a plan, orâ€¦?</h2>
      <p>
        I sometimes answer this question before someone gets the chance to ask. "Uh, Leaf, you're a
        <a href="/about">developer</a>â€¦ do you have any idea what you're doing?"
      </p>
      <p>Yes, yes I do.</p>
      <p>
        I was a writer as a kid, and I was an English major in college. Writing feels like coming
        home. I don't struggle to put words on the page.
      </p>
      <p>
        Right about now, if you were a colleague of mine in the past 20+ years, you may be thinking
        of several hundred pages of documentation that you've seen me turn out. Okayâ€¦ no problem
        with the "writing" part.
      </p>
      <p>A book, though? That's a different story from a bunch of web pages, isn't it?</p>
      <p>
        The sheer amount of writing that's in front of me isn't a problem. I did National Novel
        Writing Month (NaNoWriMo) years ago, while I was still employed. I know the volume isn't a
        problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        Organization isn't a problem. I have been organizing big stuff professionally and
        academically for years. It's just another large project. Nothing new here.
      </p>
      <p>
        What about knowledge of the publishing industry? Until a few months ago, I didn't know
        anything about book publishing. But now I'm a graduate of <a
          href="https://thebookacademy.org/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">The Book Academy</a
        >, a book writing and publishing intensive offered by 4x New York Times best-selling author, <a
          href="https://thebookacademy.org/about"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">Luvvie Ajayi Jones</a
        >.
      </p>
      <p>
        What an incredible course! Everything I could want to know about book publishing. A clear
        path for how to get there, step by step. Access to resources and contacts. A whole community
        of fellow authors for support and coworking sessions. I have no doubt that with the tools
        from this course I can do this.
      </p>

      <h2>Am I going to be in the book?</h2>
      <p>
        My favorite question so far! My coworkers asked: "have you chosen aliases for us all yet?"
      </p>
      <p>And the answer isâ€¦ maybe ðŸ˜‰</p>
      <p>
        I've learned a ton from the people I've worked with along the way. Whether they were peers,
        supervisors, mentorsâ€¦ I've been fortunate to work with some smart, talented, and wise
        people. I'm sure I'll be naming names if you've been an inspiration.
      </p>
      <p>
        Well. If you've been a <em>positive</em> inspiration. If you've been a nuisanceâ€¦ and there have
        been a fewâ€¦ I won't name those names ðŸ™‚
      </p>

      <h2>Can I be an early reader?</h2>
      <p>
        I would love to have feedback from others. I only have my own experiences, my own career
        growth, and my own research. I'd love to see how my stories and recommendations land for
        you. Keep in touch.
      </p>

      <h2>Let's do this!</h2>
      <p>
        If you want to follow along as I write and get updates about how things are going, sign up
        for my mailing list below.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: var(--content-max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--spacing-lg) 0;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 3vw, 2.5rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xl);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .book-intro {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xl);
    font-size: 1.2rem;
  }

  .book-content h2 {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-top: var(--spacing-xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .book-content p {
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
  }

  a {
    color: var(--color-accent-teal);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
</style>
